Why ISIS can exist for so long.
New York—Deadly terror attacks in Istanbul, Dhaka and Baghdad indicate ISIS's tentacles have touched multiple parts in Europe, North Africa, the Middle East, and Asia.
The longer ISIS maintains a strong presence in Syria and Iraq, the longer the days of its terrorist network concocting such massacres will be.
But ISIS is not particularly difficult to eradicate.
The problem lies in that, countries involving Iraq and Syria, including the US and its allies, have not taken ISIS as their main enemy.
This point should have changed.
ISIS has a small-scale combat force, with the United States estimating around 20,000 to 25,000 fighters in Iraq and Syria, and roughly 5,000 in Libya.
Compared to the active military personnel of Syria (125,000), Iraq (271,500), Saudi Arabia (233,500), Turkey (510,600), and Iran (523,000), ISIS is of no significance.
In September 2014, U.S. President Barack Obama vowed to "degrade and ultimately destroy" ISIS, but the U.S. and its allies, including Saudi Arabia, Turkey and Israel (in the background), have been focused on toppling Bashar Assad in Syria.
Recently, Israeli Major General Herzi Halevy has candidly stated (as quoted by a reporter who was present at Halevy's speech), "Israel does not want the Syrian situation to end with ISIS defeated, the superpowers withdrawing from the region, and Hezbollah and Iran stronger."
Israel opposes ISIS, but its greater concern is Iran behind Assad.
Assad allowed Iran to support Israel's two main non-state foes — Hezbollah and Hamas.
Therefore, Israel's priority is to overthrow Assad, not to defeat ISIS.
The Syrian civil war was, for the United States, a continuation of the plan for global American hegemony proposed by Defense Secretary Richard Cheney and Deputy Secretary of State Paul Wolfowitz at the end of the Cold War, under the influence of neoconservatism.
In 1991, Wolfowitz said to U.S. General Wesley Clark:
"But we did learn one thing from the Gulf War - that we can use force in that area, in the Middle East, and the Russians won't stop us."
"We have roughly five to ten years to clean up the old Soviet regimes — Syria, Iran (as written), Iraq."
The United States' numerous wars in the Middle East – Afghanistan, Iraq, Syria, Libya, and so on – were designed to drive the Soviet Union, and subsequently Russia, out of the competition, so that the United States would remain the sole hegemon.
These "efforts" ended in a disastrous defeat.
For Saudi Arabia, and Israel, the main goal is to overthrow Assad to weaken Iran.
Syria is part of a massive proxy war between Shia Iran and Sunni Saudi Arabia, a conflict that is unfolding in Syria and Yemen, as well as in Bahrain and other countries in the region with a propensity for sectarian divisions (including Saudi Arabia itself) where the Shia-Sunni front lines are particularly intense.
For Turkey, toppling Assad would strengthen its regional standing.
But Turkey now faces three enemies at its southern border: Assad, ISIS and the Kurdish nationalists.
So far, ISIS is not as important to Turkey as Assad and the Kurds.
But a Turkish terror attack orchestrated by ISIS might change the situation.
Russia and Iran are also pursuing their own regional interests, achieving this through proxy wars and backing militias.
Both countries have expressed their readiness to cooperate with the US to combat ISIS, and they can also cooperate on other issues.
So far, the US has been unmoved, because its focus is on toppling Assad.
The US diplomatic community has condemned Russian President Putin for shielding Assad, while Russia has condemned the US for trying to topple Assad.
These complaints look mutually biting, but in reality they are not.
The United States and its allies' attempt to overthrow Assad has violated the UN Charter, while Russia's support for Assad is in line with Syria's right to self-defense under the Charter.
Indeed, Assad is a tyrant, but the United Nations Charter does not grant any country the power to choose which tyrant to overthrow.
The persistence of ISIS highlights three strategic flaws in US foreign policy, as well as a fatal tactical flaw.
First, neoconservatism requires the overthrow of the regime to achieve US hegemony, which is not only bloody thinking of ignorance, but also a classic imperialism of overestimating oneself.
Everywhere the United States tried this, none succeeded.
Syria and Libya are the latest examples.
In addition, the CIA has for years secretly funded and armed Sunni jihadists through Saudi Arabia.
In the end, these holy warriors spawned ISIS, which was a direct (and perhaps unintended) consequence of the policy pursued by the CIA and its Saudi partners.
In large part, the United States considers Iran and Russia to be irreconcilable enemies of the United States, which is largely a self-fulfilling prophecy.
Rebuilding the relationship between the two countries is possible.
Fourthly, the US has failed in its attempt to win a two-front war against Assad and ISIS on the tactical level.
Whenever Assad is weakened, Sunni extremists, including ISIS and al-Nusra Front, will fill the vacuum.
If the US, Russia, Saudi Arabia, and Iran provided air cover and logistics support, Assad and his allies could defeat ISIS.
Indeed, Assad will continue to rule; indeed, Russia will continue to be Syria's ally; indeed, Iran will gain influence there.
Terrorist attacks will undoubtedly continue to exist, perhaps for a while under the ISIS banner; but the organization will be driven out of its operational bases in Syria and Iraq.
This outcome not only can eradicate ISIS on the Middle Eastern soil; it can also lay the foundation for a more comprehensive easing of tensions in the region.
The U.S. and Russia can start to reverse the recent new Cold War by jointly expelling the holy war terrorism.
(NATO's commitment to not allow Ukraine to join the alliance or upgrade its eastern European ballistic missile defense could have some benefits.)
There are other benefits.
Taking a cooperative approach to fight ISIS would give Saudi Arabia and Turkey a reason and opportunity to seek a new pragmatism with Iran.
Israel's security can be reinforced by allowing Iran to build a cooperative economic and geopolitical relationship with the West, thereby increasing the chances of a gradual Israeli-Palestinian reconciliation.
The rise of ISIS serves as a reflection of the strategic weaknesses, particularly of the West and the United States.
The West may be able to defeat ISIS.
The question is whether the U.S. will conduct the strategic reassessment needed to achieve this goal.
